1. **Aim to functionality**

   Your app name should provide some indication of what it **does**.

One idea is to pair the basic function of the app with a word that enhances it and adds originality. Some good examples are *Wunderlist*, *Evernote* and *Tweetbot*. **Clarity** and **recognisability** are quite important. Take this into account when deciding on a name.

4. **Use Real Words**

For your app to gain *momentum* and popularity, people need to be able  to talk about it in the real world. 

While  you have complete licence to make up new words, use caution when making words that are hard to say and be aware of the impact this will have on  how easy the name is to remember. It's certainly possible to have your app reach legendary status without an easy to say name, but again, why  take your chances in it becoming popular *in spite* of that?

5. **Stick to sentence case**

If you notice your collection of apps, most use sentence-case (e.g. 
Candy Crush Saga) or camel-case (e.g. WhatsApp). It may sound like a 
good idea to differentiate by starting your app name with a lowercase 
letter or opting for all-caps, in reality, this can delegitimise your 
app quicker. People will buy what they trust, and breaking the 
upper/lower convention is a quick way to make your app look sketchy.

Just verify if that name hasn't been attribuited to **another** **app**. Not so much about the legal ramifications, it's more about setting your app appart from what could be a widely recognised name in the **future**. 

Get on Google and **research** every last permutation of your name.  It may be a bummer to have to go back to the drawing board, but it will  save you some headaches later on.



7. **Find the right length**

Keep your name short and concise. Long names are arduous to read,  difficult to remember, and won't look right in someone's collection of apps. However, with **really** short names you may **struggle** to find  something that hasn't already been used.

Throw Twitter handles and  domain names into the mix and the range of available names becomes even narrower. A smart way to differentiate your app name is by getting creative with prefixes and suffixes. An '**app**' suffix makes it clear what  your product does, while prefixes like '**go**' or '**get**' can invoke action.
